FILED SENATE
Mar 20, 2025
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
S.B. 357
SESSION 2025
PRINCIPAL CLERK
S D
SENATE BILL DRS45186-NB-17
Short Title: Pharmacists/Collaborative Practice. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Sawrey, Hise, and Galey (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MODERNIZE AND EXPAND PHYSICIAN-PHARMACIST
3 COLLABORATIVE PRACTICE.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 90-18(c)(3a) reads as rewritten:
6 "(3a) The provision of drug therapy management by a licensed pharmacist engaged
7 in the practice of pharmacy pursuant to an agreement that is physician,
8 pharmacist, patient, and disease specific when health care services by a
9 licensed pharmacist under a collaborative practice agreement with one or
10 more physicians shall be performed in accordance with rules and rules
11 developed by a joint subcommittee of the North Carolina Medical Board and
12 the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy and approved by both Boards. Drug
13 therapy management shall be defined as: (i) the implementation of
14 predetermined drug therapy which includes diagnosis and product selection
15 by the patient's physician; (ii) modification of prescribed drug dosages, dosage
16 forms, and dosage schedules; and (iii) ordering tests; (i), (ii), and (iii) shall be
17 pursuant to an agreement that is physician, pharmacist, patient, and disease
18 specific.For the purposes of this subdivision, "health care services" means
19 medical tasks, acts, or functions authorized through a written agreement by a
20 physician and delegated to a pharmacist for the purpose of providing drug
21 therapy, disease, or population health management for patients."
22 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 90-18.4 reads as rewritten:
23 "§ 90-18.4. Limitations on clinical pharmacist practitioners.
24 (a) Any pharmacist who is approved under the provisions of G.S. 90-18(c)(3a) to perform
25 medical acts, tasks, and functions may use the title "clinical pharmacist practitioner". Any other
26 person who uses the title in any form or holds himself or herself out to be a clinical pharmacist
27 practitioner or to be so licensed shall be deemed to be in violation of this Article.
28 (b) Clinical pharmacist practitioners are authorized to implement predetermined drug
29 therapy, which includes diagnosis and product selection by the patient's physician, modify
30 prescribed drug dosages, dosage forms, and dosage schedules, and to order laboratory tests
31 pursuant to a drug therapy management agreement that is physician, pharmacist, patient, and
32 disease specific by physicians to provide health care services in accordance with
33 G.S. 90-18(c)(3a) and subsection (e) of this section under the following conditions:
34 (1) The North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy
35 have adopted rules developed by a joint subcommittee governing the approval
36 of individual clinical pharmacist practitioners to practice drug therapy
*DRS45186-NB-17*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 management health care services with such limitations that the Boards
2 determine to be in the best interest of patient health and safety.
3 (2) The clinical pharmacist practitioner has current approval from both Boards.
4 (3) The North Carolina Medical Board has assigned an identification number to
5 the clinical pharmacist practitioner which is shown on written prescriptions
6 written by the clinical pharmacist practitioner.
7 (4) The drug therapy management agreement prohibits the substitution of a
8 chemically dissimilar drug product by the pharmacist for the product
9 prescribed by the physician without the explicit consent of the physician and
10 includes a policy for periodic review by the physician of the drugs modified
11 pursuant to the agreement or changed with the consent of the physician.
12 (c) Clinical pharmacist practitioners in hospitals and other health facilities that have an
13 established pharmacy and therapeutics committee or similar group that determines the
14 prescription drug formulary or other list of drugs to be utilized in the facility and determines
15 procedures to be followed when considering a drug for inclusion on the formulary and procedures
16 to acquire a nonformulary drug for a patient may order medications and tests under the following
17 conditions:
18 (1) The North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy
19 have adopted rules governing the approval of individual clinical pharmacist
20 practitioners to order medications and tests with such limitations as the Boards
21 determine to be in the best interest of patient health and safety.
22 (2) The clinical pharmacist practitioner has current approval from both Boards.
23 (3) The supervising physician has provided to the clinical pharmacist practitioner
24 written instructions for ordering, changing, or substituting drugs, or ordering
25 tests with provision for review of the order by the physician within a
26 reasonable time, as determined by the Boards, after the medication or tests are
27 ordered.
28 (4) The hospital or health facility has adopted a written policy, approved by the
29 medical staff after consultation with nursing administrators, concerning the
30 ordering of medications and tests, including procedures for verification of the
31 clinical pharmacist practitioner's orders by nurses and other facility employees
32 and such other procedures that are in the best interest of patient health and
33 safety.
34 (5)(c1) Any drug therapy order written by a clinical pharmacist practitioner or order for
35 medications or tests medications, tests, or devices shall be deemed to have been authorized by
36 the physician approved by the Boards as the supervisor of the clinical pharmacist practitioner and
37 the supervising physician shall be responsible for authorizing the prescription order.
38 (c2) Institutional and group practices may implement a site-specific, multi-provider
39 collaborative practice agreement for the care of their patients. The institution or group practice
40 must develop a policy for oversight, and the clinical pharmacist practitioners engaged in the
41 agreement must be evaluated by an appointed supervising physician.
42 (d) Any registered nurse or nurse, licensed practical nurse nurse, or pharmacist who
43 receives a drug therapy therapy, laboratory test, or device order from a clinical pharmacist
44 practitioner for medications or tests is authorized to perform that order in the same manner as if
45 the order was received from a licensed physician.
46 (e) The following requirements apply to clinical pharmacist practitioners and supervising
47 physicians engaging in collaborative practice:
48 (1) A clinical pharmacist practitioner shall have a site-specific supervising
49 physician.
50 (2) The supervising physician shall conduct periodic review and evaluation of the
51 health care services provided by the clinical pharmacist practitioner.
Page 2 DRS45186-NB-17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) A physician may collaborate with any number of clinical pharmacist
2 practitioners, but when acting as the supervising physician, they shall
3 supervise as many clinical pharmacist practitioners as the supervising
4 physician deems can be safely and effectively supervised.
5 (4) Health care services delegated by a supervising physician, such as initiating,
6 changing, or discontinuing drugs, or ordering tests or devices, to assist with
7 drug therapy, disease, or population health management, must be included in
8 the written agreement between the supervising physician and the clinical
9 pharmacist practitioner.
10 (5) A supervising physician may include a "statement of authorization" in the
11 written agreement to allow the clinical pharmacist practitioner to conduct drug
12 substitutions within the same therapeutic class or for biosimilar medications
13 based upon the health plan's drug formulary for a patient. The clinical
14 pharmacist practitioner shall document and notify the patient's physician of
15 any substitutions made.
16 (6) Supervising physicians may add other advanced practice providers that they
17 supervise to their collaborative practice agreement with a clinical pharmacist
18 practitioner. The evaluation and supervision of the clinical pharmacist
19 practitioner shall remain with the supervising physician.
20 (f) The health care setting location for the provision of health care services by the clinical
21 pharmacist practitioner may be fully or partially embedded for a site-specific practice. The setting
22 location shall be determined by the supervising physician and included in the site-specific
23 collaborative practice agreement."
24 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 90-85.3(b2) reads as rewritten:
25 "(b2) "Clinical pharmacist practitioner" means a licensed pharmacist who meets the
26 guidelines and criteria for such title established by the joint subcommittee of the North Carolina
27 Medical Board and the North Carolina Board of Pharmacy and is authorized to enter into perform
28 medical acts, tasks, and functions for drug therapy therapy, disease, or population health
29 management agreements with physicians in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 90-18.4."
30 SECTION 2.(a) Part 7 of Article 50 of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended
31 by adding a new section to read:
32 "§ 58-50-296. Pharmacist credentialing.
33 Insurers offering a health benefit plan that delegates credentialing agreements or
34 requirements for pharmacists licensed under Article 4A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes or
35 the relevant laws of another state to a contracted healthcare facility shall accept the credentialing
36 for all pharmacists employed by, or contracted with, those healthcare facilities."
37 SECTION 2.(b) Article 3 of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by
38 adding a new section to read:
39 "§ 58-3-241. Healthcare services provided by pharmacists.
40 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
41 (1) Healthcare services. – Any of the following health or medical procedures or
42 services rendered by a healthcare provider:
43 a. Testing, diagnosis, or treatment of a health condition, illness, injury,
44 or disease. This includes testing, diagnosis, or treatment rendered by a
45 pharmacist acting within the pharmacist's scope of practice.
46 b. Dispensing of drugs, medical devices, medical appliances, or medical
47 goods for the treatment of a health condition, illness, injury, or disease.
48 c. Administration of a vaccine or medication.
49 (2) Pharmacist. – An individual licensed to practice pharmacy under Article 4A
50 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes or the relevant laws of another state.
DRS45186-NB-17 Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) A health benefit plan offered by an insurer in this State shall cover healthcare services
2 provided by a pharmacist if all of the following conditions are met:
3 (1) The service or procedure was performed within the pharmacist's licensed
4 lawful scope of practice.
5 (2) The health benefit plan would have covered the service if the service or
6 procedure had been performed by another healthcare provider.
7 (c) The participation of a pharmacy in a drug benefit provider network of a health benefit
8 plan shall not satisfy any requirement that insurers offering health benefit plans include
9 pharmacists in medical benefit provider networks."
10 SECTION 2.(c) G.S. 58-56-26 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
11 "(e) Notwithstanding any provision of this Article to the contrary, all requirements relating
12 to the coverage of prescription drugs and pharmacy services under this Chapter applicable to
13 health benefit plans are applicable to a third-party administrator in the same way they are
14 applicable to an insurer."
15 SECTION 2.(d) Article 56A of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by
16 adding a new section to read:
17 "§ 58-56A-55. Health benefit plan requirements applicable.
18 All requirements relating to the coverage of prescription drugs and pharmacy services under
19 this Chapter applicable to health benefit plans are applicable to a pharmacy benefits manager in
20 the same way they are applicable to an insurer."
21 SECTION 2.(e) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
22 contracts entered into, renewed, or amended on or after that date.
23 SECTION 3.(a) The North Carolina Medical Board and the North Carolina Board
24 of Pharmacy may adopt temporary rules to implement the provisions of this act.
25 SECTION 3.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law.
26 SECTION 4. Except as otherwise provided, this act becomes effective October 1,
27 2025.
